# 📊 3. The ONLY things that repeat in markets

These are the **real edges you listed** — let’s go deeper:

---

## 📈 A. Distribution of Returns


Markets don’t move randomly — they follow **distributions**:

* Not perfectly normal (Gaussian)
* They have **fat tails** (extreme events happen more than expected)

👉 Edge example:

* If returns cluster around a mean → mean reversion strategy works
* If tails are fat → risk management becomes alpha

---

## ⚡ B. Volatility Clustering

This is one of the **strongest edges in all markets**:

> High volatility → tends to stay high
> Low volatility → tends to stay low

This is tied to:

* Autoregressive Conditional Heteroskedasticity
* GARCH Model

👉 Edge example:

* After volatility expansion → expect continuation of large moves
* After compression → expect breakout

---

## 🔁 C. Mean Reversion Windows

Prices tend to revert to:

* VWAP
* Value Area (Volume Profile)
* Moving averages

But **ONLY in certain regimes**.

👉 Edge example:

* In balanced markets → fade extremes
* In trending markets → this edge fails

---

## 🚀 D. Trend Persistence (Regime Dependent)

Trends exist — but not always.

Markets switch between:

* **Trend regime**
* **Mean-reversion regime**

👉 Edge example:

* Momentum works ONLY in trend regimes
* Fails badly in chop

---

# 🧮 4. Why this works (the math foundation)

## 🔢 Law of Large Numbers

> As sample size increases → your actual results converge to expected value

So:

* 1 trade = noise
* 1000 trades = signal

---

## 📊 Central Limit Theorem

> The average of outcomes becomes normally distributed over time

Even if:

* Individual trades are chaotic
* Outcomes are skewed

👉 Your **equity curve becomes predictable**

---

# ⚙️ 5. What an “edge” looks like numerically

Example:

* Win rate: 55%
* Risk/Reward: 1:1

Expected value:

[
EV = (0.55 \times 1) - (0.45 \times 1) = 0.10
]

That means:

* +0.10 per trade (on average)
* Over 1000 trades → +100 units

👉 THIS is the edge — not the individual trade

